[Due to technical difficulties we are unable to provide a veterinary health
moderator comment on these reports at this time. We apologize for this
inconvenience. That being said, this moderator would like to request more
information on this suspected outbreak of H5N2 in South Korea. According
to the newswires, final testing results of pathogenicity (high vs. low)
should be available on Thurs (23 Dec 2004).
Mod. AS' comment in Avian influenza, A/H5N2 - Taiwan: suspected
20040116.0169 seems appropriate to repeat here: "From this news item it is
not clear whether this incident, and the identification of an A/H5N2 avian
influenza virus, may be regarded as a case of HPAI (highly pathogenic avian
influenza); the clinical findings are not described. However, one should
take into consideration that an HPAI A/H5N2 virus, which caused a serious
outbreak in northern Italy in 1997/1998, was found -- in phylogenetic
analysis of the haemagglutinin (HA) genes -- to cluster with the A/H5N1,
HPAI Hong Kong strains which had infected humans. (See: Isabella Donatelli,
et al. Characterization of H5N2 influenza viruses from Italian poultry. J
Gen Virol 2001; 82: 623ï¿½30. <http://vir.sgmjournals.org/>). During 1994/5,
an A/H5N2 virus was involved in a serious avian influenza outbreak in
Mexico (see references). Complementary information, and official
confirmation from the [South Korean] authorities, are needed." - Mods.MPP/DK]
